#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:10
msgid "2.1 A Brief Recap: Linear Neurons and Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:12
msgid ""
"The previous chapter situated the Boltzmann machine within the conceptual"
" landscape of statistical physics—a landscape defined by energy "
"functions, equilibrium distributions, and thermal fluctuations. Before we"
" delve deeper into energy-based learning, it is essential to revisit the "
"elementary building blocks of neural computation. Understanding the "
"simplest neuron models, their capabilities, and—crucially—their "
"limitations provides the necessary contrast to appreciate why the "
"Boltzmann machine adopts such a radically different computational "
"paradigm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:14
msgid "<b>The Linear Neuron: Weighted Sum and Threshold</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:16
msgid ""
"The most basic computational unit in neural networks is the <b>linear "
"neuron</b> (also called a <em>linear threshold unit</em> or, "
"historically, a <em>McCulloch-Pitts neuron</em>). Its operation is "
"straightforward: it computes a weighted sum of its inputs and produces an"
" output based on whether that sum exceeds a threshold."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:18
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Let $\\mathbf{x} = (x_1, x_2, \\ldots, x_d)$ be a vector of input values."
" Each input $x_j$ is multiplied by a corresponding <b>weight</b> $w_j$, "
"representing the strength of the synaptic connection. An additional "
"<b>bias</b> term $b$ shifts the decision boundary. The neuron's output "
"$y$ is given by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:20
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"y = \\begin{cases}1 & \\text{if } \\sum_{j=1}^d w_j x_j + b \\geq 0 \\\\0"
" & \\text{otherwise}\\end{cases}"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:22
msgid "Equivalently, we can write this as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:24
#, python-brace-format
msgid "y = \\mathbb{I}\\left( \\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} + b \\geq 0 \\right)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:26
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"where $\\mathbb{I}(\\cdot)$ is the indicator function. The vector $ "
"\\mathbf{w} = (w_1, \\ldots, w_d)$ is called the <b>weight vector</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:28
msgid "<b>Geometric Interpretation: Linear Separability</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:30
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The linear neuron has a clear geometric interpretation. The equation "
"$\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} + b = 0$ defines a <b>hyperplane</b> in "
"the $d$-dimensional input space. This hyperplane partitions the space "
"into two half-spaces:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:32
msgid "Points on one side produce an output of 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:33
msgid "Points on the other side produce an output of 0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:35
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The weight vector $\\mathbf{w}$ is perpendicular to the hyperplane and "
"points toward the positive half-space. The bias $b$ determines the "
"perpendicular distance from the origin to the hyperplane (specifically, "
"distance $= -b / \\|\\mathbf{w}\\|$)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:37
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"This geometric view immediately reveals the fundamental capability and "
"the fundamental limitation of linear neurons. A linear neuron can "
"successfully classify any dataset that is <b>linearly separable, "
"</b>which means there exists some hyperplane that perfectly separates the"
" positive examples (label 1) from the negative examples (label 0). For "
"such problems, there exist weight vectors $\\mathbf{w}$ and biases $b$ "
"that achieve perfect accuracy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:39
msgid "<b>The Perceptron Learning Algorithm</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:41
msgid ""
"The <b>perceptron</b> is a specific training algorithm for linear "
"threshold units, introduced by Frank Rosenblatt in 1958. It provides a "
"simple, iterative procedure for finding a separating hyperplane, "
"<em>provided one exists</em>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:43
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The perceptron learning rule processes training examples one at a time. "
"For each example $(\\mathbf{x}, t)$, where $t \\in \\{0,1\\}$ is the "
"target label, the algorithm:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:45
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Computes the current output: $y = \\mathbb{I}(\\mathbf{w}^\\top "
"\\mathbf{x} + b \\geq 0)$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:46
msgid "If $y = t$, the weights remain unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:47
msgid "If $y \\neq t$, the weights are updated as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:48
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"If $t = 1$ but $y = 0$ (false negative): $\\mathbf{w} \\leftarrow "
"\\mathbf{w} + \\eta \\mathbf{x}$, $b \\leftarrow b + \\eta$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:49
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"If $t = 0$ but $y = 1$ (false positive): $\\mathbf{w} \\leftarrow "
"\\mathbf{w} - \\eta \\mathbf{x}$, $b \\leftarrow b - \\eta$."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:51
msgid ""
"Here, $\\eta > 0$ is the <b>learning rate</b>, a small positive constant "
"controlling the step size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:53
msgid ""
"The <b>Perceptron Convergence Theorem</b> guarantees that if the training"
" data are linearly separable, this algorithm will find a separating "
"hyperplane in a finite number of steps. This theoretical guarantee, "
"proven in the early 1960s, generated enormous enthusiasm for neural "
"network research."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:55
msgid "<b>The Limits of Linear Separability: The XOR Problem</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:57
msgid ""
"The enthusiasm was short-lived. In 1969, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert"
" published their influential book <em>Perceptrons</em>, which rigorously "
"analyzed the capabilities and limitations of linear threshold units. "
"Their most famous counterexample is the <b>XOR (exclusive-or)</b> "
"problem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:59
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"Consider two binary inputs $x_1, x_2 \\in \\{0,1\\}$ and the desired "
"outputs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md
msgid "$$x_1$$"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md
msgid "$$x_2$$"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md
msgid "<b>XOR Output</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md
msgid "0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md
msgid "1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:68
msgid ""
"Plotting these four points in the 2D input plane reveals the difficulty. "
"The positive examples, (0,1) and (1,0), are diagonally opposite; the "
"negative examples, (0,0) and (1,1), occupy the other diagonal. <b>No "
"single straight line can separate the two classes.</b> The XOR function "
"is not linearly separable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:70
msgid ""
"Minsky and Papert proved that this limitation extends far beyond XOR. "
"Linear threshold units fail on any function that requires a <em>non-"
"convex</em> decision boundary or one with disconnected regions. Many "
"seemingly simple logical functions, i.e. parity, connectedness in visual "
"patterns are beyond the reach of a single perceptron."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:72
msgid "<b>The Historical Impact: The First AI Winter</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:74
msgid ""
"The rigorous demonstration of the perceptron's limitations had a chilling"
" effect on neural network research throughout the 1970s. Funding dried "
"up, and many researchers abandoned connectionist approaches in favor of "
"symbolic artificial intelligence. This period is often referred to as the"
" <b>first AI winter</b>."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:76
msgid ""
"The core insight from this episode, however, was not that neural networks"
" were fundamentally flawed, but that <b>single-layer linear networks are "
"insufficient for complex tasks</b>. The path forward required two "
"essential innovations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:78
msgid ""
"<b>Multiple Layers</b>: Stacking linear threshold units into layers, with"
" the outputs of one layer serving as inputs to the next, can overcome the"
" linear separability limitation. A two-layer network can represent any "
"Boolean function; with continuous activation functions, deeper networks "
"can approximate arbitrarily complex decision boundaries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:79
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"<b>Nonlinear Activation Functions</b>: The step function $\\mathbb{I}(z "
"\\geq 0)$ is discontinuous and non-differentiable. Replacing it with "
"smooth, differentiable nonlinearities—such as the <b>sigmoid</b> "
"$\\sigma(z) = 1/(1+e^{-z})$ or the <b>hyperbolic tangent</b> $\\tanh(z)$,"
" enables gradient-based learning through <b>backpropagation</b>, a topic "
"we will revisit in the context of energy-based models."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:81
msgid "<b>From Feedforward Classification to Probabilistic Generation</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:83
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The perceptron and its multilayer successors are fundamentally "
"<b>discriminative models</b>: they learn a direct mapping from inputs "
"$\\mathbf{x}$ to outputs $y$. Their objective is to minimize "
"classification errors on a labeled dataset. The computation is "
"<b>feedforward</b>: information flows in one direction, from input to "
"output, without cycles or recurrence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:85
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"The Boltzmann machine, in stark contrast, belongs to the family of "
"<b>generative models</b>. Its objective is not to map inputs to outputs "
"but to model the <em>joint probability distribution</em> $P(\\mathbf{x})$"
" (or $P(\\mathbf{x}, \\mathbf{h})$ with hidden units) of the observed "
"data. The computation is <b>recurrent</b>: units are interconnected "
"symmetrically, and the network's state evolves over time through "
"stochastic updates until equilibrium is reached."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:87
msgid ""
"Why abandon the simplicity of feedforward classification for the "
"complexity of recurrent, stochastic, energy-based models? The answer lies"
" in the types of problems each paradigm addresses. Perceptrons excel at "
"<em>supervised pattern recognition</em> when large labeled datasets are "
"available. Boltzmann machines address <em>unsupervised learning</em> and "
"<em>generation</em>: discovering the underlying structure of data without"
" explicit labels, completing missing information, and synthesizing new, "
"plausible examples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:89
msgid ""
"The limitations of linear neurons taught us that simple, shallow "
"architectures cannot capture the rich structure of natural data. The "
"Boltzmann machine answers this lesson not by stacking deterministic "
"layers, but by embracing a fundamentally different computational "
"metaphor—one drawn from the statistical physics of complex systems, where"
" global structure emerges from local, stochastic interactions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:91
msgid "<b>Connection to Energy-Based Models</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:93
#, python-brace-format
msgid ""
"As we transition to the next section, note a subtle but important "
"parallel. The perceptron's decision rule $\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} +"
" b \\geq 0$ can be reinterpreted in energetic terms. Define an "
"<b>energy</b> for a given input-output pair:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:95
#, python-brace-format
msgid "E(\\mathbf{x}, y) = -y (\\mathbf{w}^\\top \\mathbf{x} + b)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:97
msgid ""
"The perceptron outputs $y=1$ when this energy is negative (i.e., low), "
"and $y=0$ when it is zero (i.e., higher). The learning rule adjusts "
"weights to lower the energy of correct classifications and raises the "
"energy of incorrect ones."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:99
msgid ""
"This energy-based perspective, while rudimentary in the perceptron, "
"becomes the central organizing principle in Boltzmann machines. The "
"difference is that Boltzmann machines define energy over <em>all</em> "
"units, both visible and hidden and use stochastic, rather than "
"deterministic, state transitions to explore the energy landscape. The "
"following sections will develop this energy-based viewpoint in full "
"mathematical detail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:101
msgid "<b>Summary</b>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:103
msgid ""
"A <b>linear neuron</b> computes a weighted sum of inputs and applies a "
"threshold, partitioning the input space with a hyperplane."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:104
msgid ""
"The <b>perceptron algorithm</b> provably finds a separating hyperplane "
"for linearly separable data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:105
msgid ""
"The <b>XOR problem</b> demonstrates that single linear threshold units "
"cannot solve non-linearly separable tasks, triggering the first AI "
"winter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:106
msgid ""
"Overcoming this limitation requires either <b>multiple layers</b> of "
"nonlinear units or a fundamentally different computational paradigm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:107
msgid ""
"The <b>Boltzmann machine</b> chooses the latter path: a "
"<b>generative</b>, <b>recurrent</b>, and <b>energy-based</b> architecture"
" capable of unsupervised learning and probabilistic inference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/kpp-theoretical-foundations/kpp-theoretical-foundations-nn-recap.md:108
msgid ""
"The transition from deterministic perceptrons to stochastic Boltzmann "
"machines parallels a shift from <b>discriminative classification</b> to "
"<b>probabilistic modeling</b> of data distributions."
msgstr ""

